  "concept": "This is the unit that unlocks real sentences. About 90% of French verbs end in -er, and they (almost) all follow ONE pattern. Learn it once and you can say thousands of things.\n\nTake the verb parler (to speak). Drop the -er and add these endings:\n  je parle, tu parles, il/elle parle,\n  nous parlons, vous parlez, ils/elles parlent.\n\nTwo things surprise beginners. First, the -ent ending on ils/elles is SILENT — « ils parlent » sounds exactly like « il parle ». In fact je, tu, il and ils forms all sound identical; only the spelling changes. Second, before a vowel or a silent h, je becomes j': j'aime, j'habite, j'écoute.\n\nThe same endings work for habiter (to live), aimer (to like/love), écouter (to listen to), regarder (to watch), travailler (to work), jouer (to play), and hundreds more.\n\nTo say what you like, use aimer + the definite article (le / la / les): j'aime le sport, j'aime la musique, j'aime les langues. Note that French keeps the article where English drops it — not « j'aime sport » but « j'aime le sport ». Add beaucoup for emphasis: j'aime beaucoup le cinéma.\n\nWith these verbs you can finally build full sentences about your life: where you live, what you study, what you like. Write three true sentences about yourself using three different -er verbs.",
